So, I feel conflicted just explaining my reasoning as it seems insensitive in the current situation. As such, I will just give the basic gist of it - considering age, rapidity and suspected extent of symptom onset, and existing risk factors a certain relatively high risk of not recovering exits. Adding some additional factors such as rapid access to high-level treatments and care likely decreases this risk some. There is a larger possibility of recovery but it could be a long one lasting weeks to months. Since there is a strong desire to have public visibility during final weeks before a contentious election, I feel there is a much higher chance of having 2 debates but a much smaller one of having all three. So many high level individuals in government and RNC have been exposed in close quarters without masks, and the count of those infected is rising extremely rapidly. It takes 2 weeks to allow all of those exposed the time to develop symptoms. What about others who carry out essential daily functions at the WH? The hundreds of people who attended the rose garden event? Everyone exposed at the events between Saturday and Thursday? All of their families? This could be much more than a small ripple - it could be a tsunami. The remaining debates would most certainly shift the focus back to the pandemic, which is what the RNC has been trying to avoid from the onset.

There are currently 3 debates scheduled in September and October, despite 2020 being an odd year, I do not see why there should be anything less than 3 debates.

In the past three presidential election cycles (2008, 2012, and 2016) there were a total of three debates between the front-runners (not including VP and non-sanctioned/unofficial debates). These all occurred either in late September or October, a period which is still over a month and a half away. So historically, it would seem 2-3 debates would be most likely, with 0-1 being virtually unheard of in modern political history. Biden has also committed to all three scheduled debates (he did so in June), further increasing the chances all three are held. However, there are several reasons that less than three debates would be held. First, there is the pandemic, which will change the possible optics of a debate and won't allow candidates to exude as much confidence/competence (picture Trump following Clinton around the stage versus Trump crouched over in front of a laptop). With candidates swapping jabs about cognitive ability and old age, such optics may lead to one or both sides excusing themselves from later debates. Similarly, Trump is currently finding as many ways as possible to get in front of cameras and speak to the American people. The debates would give him another avenue to do this. However, as we saw with his COVID task force briefings, he will forego the limelight if doing otherwise may tarnish his image (bleach, anyone?). So, if the first or second debate goes exceptionally poorly in one way or another (doubtful, but possible), we may not make it to the final debate(s).
Both sides benefit from wanting a debate, and both have high probability of a fubar in a debate. I will refine forecast with more information.
